# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1901-in-canadian-football
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1901-in-canadian-football/1882-in-canadian-football] The following is an overview of the events of **1882 in Canadian football**, primarily focusing on the senior teams that played in this era.
[src:1901-in-canadian-football/1882-in-canadian-football] This includes news, playoff games, and championships.
[src:1901-in-canadian-football/1882-in-canadian-football] In Quebec, the season of 1882 opened on May 13 with the Britannia Football Club and Montreal Football Club playing to a 0–0 tie.
[src:1901-in-canadian-football/1882-in-canadian-football] On October 4, the Britannia Football Club and Royal Military College Foot-Ball Club scored a goal but it was another 1–1 tie and the Brits were undefeated.
[src:1901-in-canadian-football/1882-in-canadian-football] On October 21, they defeated their cross-town rivals, Montreal one goal to nil, and then defeated McGill two goals to nil to again capture the city championship.
[src:1901-in-canadian-football/1883-in-canadian-football] The following is an overview of the events of **1883 in Canadian football**, primarily focusing on the senior teams that played in this era.
[src:1901-in-canadian-football/1883-in-canadian-football] This includes news, standings, playoff games, and championships.
[src:1901-in-canadian-football/1883-in-canadian-football] This was the first season of the creation of the Ontario Rugby Football Union (ORFU) and the Quebec Rugby Football Union (QRFU).
[src:1901-in-canadian-football/1883-in-canadian-football] In this season, a point scoring system was established where a goal from field was worth six points, a try was worth four points, a safety was worth two points, and kicks to the deadline and rouges were worth one point.
[src:1901-in-canadian-football/1883-in-canadian-football] Each team had 15 players on the field at a time and each game was composed of two 45-minute halves.
[src:1901-in-canadian-football/1883-in-canadian-football] The Ontario Rugby Football Union was formed on January 6, 1883, and the Quebec Rugby Football Union would organize ten days later.
[src:1901-in-canadian-football/1884-in-canadian-football] The following is an overview of the events of **1884 in Canadian football**, primarily focusing on the senior teams that played in this era.
[src:1901-in-canadian-football/1884-in-canadian-football] This was the second season since the creation of the Ontario Rugby Football Union (ORFU) and the Quebec Rugby Football Union (QRFU) in 1883 and the first since the re-establishment of the Canadian Rugby Football Union (CRFU).
[src:1901-in-canadian-football/1884-in-canadian-football] The season was highlighted by the first ever Rugby Football Dominion Championship where the Montreal Football Club defeated the Toronto Football Club by a score of 30 to 0.
[src:1901-in-canadian-football/1884-in-canadian-football] On February 7, 1884, the Canadian Rugby Football Union was formed to provide a regulatory body for Rugby Football in Canada along with establishing a national championship game.
[src:1901-in-canadian-football/1884-in-canadian-football] The QRFU adopted a point based system this year, adopting the ORFU model, as opposed to the previous year where they recorded the number of tries and goals scored.
[src:1901-in-canadian-football/1884-in-canadian-football] The Montreal Football Club and the Britannia Football Club played for the Quebec Challenge Cup.
[src:1901-in-canadian-football/1884-in-canadian-football] The teams proved evenly matched with Montreal only scoring one rouge in the entire game while the Brits did not score.
[src:1901-in-canadian-football/1884-in-canadian-football] Since Montreal did not record enough points, the game ended in a draw.
[src:1901-in-canadian-football/1884-in-canadian-football] Because Britannia was not able to defeat Montreal, Montreal retained their Quebec title and were declared the champions of Quebec.
[src:1901-in-canadian-football/1884-in-canadian-football] At the beginning of the season, 14 Ontario rugby clubs were eligible to compete for the Ontario Challenge Cup.
[src:1901-in-canadian-football/1884-in-canadian-football] Five of these clubs either did not participate or forfeited immediately.
[src:1901-in-canadian-football/1884-in-canadian-football] The remaining nine teams competed in a series of sudden death matches until one undefeated team remained, being named the Ontario Rugby Challenge Cup champion.
[src:1901-in-canadian-football/1884-in-canadian-football] Prior to the scheduled final between Toronto and Ottawa, Ottawa declared forfeit due to seven of their players being unable to make the trip to Toronto.
[src:1901-in-canadian-football/1884-in-canadian-football] Given the short notice, since the Toronto club received the telegram one day before the scheduled match, the integrity of the Ottawa club was questioned since they had at least 35 members and appeared reluctant to send a replacement team that would only lose.
[src:1901-in-canadian-football/1884-in-canadian-football] Since tickets had been paid for, Toronto attempted to schedule a match with Hamilton, but were refused due to the justifiably short notice.
[src:1901-in-canadian-football/1884-in-canadian-football] Consequently, the Toronto Football Club were Ontario Challenge Cup champions due to Ottawa's forfeit.
[src:1901-in-canadian-football/1885-in-canadian-football] The following is an overview of the events of **1885 in Canadian football**, primarily focusing on the senior teams that played in this era.
[src:1901-in-canadian-football/1885-in-canadian-football] This was the third season since the creation of the Ontario Rugby Football Union (ORFU) and the Quebec Rugby Football Union (QRFU) and the second since the re-establishment of the Canadian Rugby Football Union (CRFU).
[src:1901-in-canadian-football/1885-in-canadian-football] In this season, the Canadian Rugby Football Union (CRFU) established a standard field size of 100 yards long by 65 yards wide.
[src:1901-in-canadian-football/1886-in-canadian-football] The following is an overview of the events of **1886 in Canadian football**, primarily focusing on the senior teams that played in this era.
[src:1901-in-canadian-football/1886-in-canadian-football] This was the fourth season since the creation of the Ontario Rugby Football Union (ORFU) and the Quebec Rugby Football Union (QRFU) and the second since the re-establishment of the Canadian Rugby Football Union (CRFU).
[src:1901-in-canadian-football/1886-in-canadian-football] There was no Canadian championship this year.
[src:1901-in-canadian-football/1886-in-canadian-football] Initially, the Canadian Rugby Football Union (CRFU) had scheduled a second consecutive All-Star game to be played in Montreal on November 18, 1886.
[src:1901-in-canadian-football/1886-in-canadian-football] However, the ORFU was opposed and preferred a championship game between their champions and the champions of the QRFU.
[src:1901-in-canadian-football/1886-in-canadian-football] Additionally, the ORFU was disputing a proposed rule change that would allow for passing the ball back through the scrimmage, which was a significant deviation from rugby football.
[src:1901-in-canadian-football/1886-in-canadian-football] Consequently, the ORFU informed the QRFU winners, the Montreal Football Club, via telegram on November 15, that they would not be sending a team.
[src:1901-in-canadian-football/1886-in-canadian-football] At the CRFU annual meeting on November 18, the aforementioned rule change was adopted.
[src:1901-in-canadian-football/1887-in-canadian-football] The following is an overview of the events of **1887 in Canadian football**, primarily focusing on the senior teams that played in this era.
[src:1901-in-canadian-football/1887-in-canadian-football] This was the fifth season since the creation of the Ontario Rugby Football Union (ORFU) and the Quebec Rugby Football Union (QRFU).
[src:1901-in-canadian-football/1887-in-canadian-football] The ORFU withdrew from the Canadian Rugby Football Union (CRFU) and the governing body ceased to function.
[src:1901-in-canadian-football/1887-in-canadian-football] The St.John's Rugby Football Club (St.John's) formed in October 1887.
[src:1901-in-canadian-football/1887-in-canadian-football] John's team met the Winnipeg Football Club (Winnipegs) to determine the first ever Manitoba champions.
[src:1901-in-canadian-football/1887-in-canadian-football] After splitting the first two games, a third game was scheduled to determine the winner.
[src:1901-in-canadian-football/1887-in-canadian-football] The Winnipegs won by a goal and a try to nil.
[src:1901-in-canadian-football/1887-in-canadian-football] All games were scored using the challenge system which credited the team with the most goals as the winner.
[src:1901-in-canadian-football/1887-in-canadian-football] The games were unofficially scored using the points system used by the CRU in eastern Canada.
[src:1901-in-canadian-football/1887-in-canadian-football] Based on the points system, the Winnipegs won all three games.
[src:1901-in-canadian-football/1888-in-canadian-football] The following is an overview of the events of **1888 in Canadian football**, primarily focusing on the senior teams that played in this era.
[src:1901-in-canadian-football/1888-in-canadian-football] This was the sixth season since the creation of the Ontario Rugby Football Union (ORFU) and the Quebec Rugby Football Union (QRFU).
[src:1901-in-canadian-football/1888-in-canadian-football] As a three-time champion, Ottawa College was awarded the ORFU Championship, provided that they defend it from challenges.
[src:1901-in-canadian-football/1888-in-canadian-football] Teams in the ORFU played for the right to contest, with the Hamilton Tigers emerging as the victor.
[src:1901-in-canadian-football/1888-in-canadian-football] However, the Ottawa College defense still handled them with ease and the team won 10–1.
[src:1901-in-canadian-football/1888-in-canadian-football] With the Canadian Rugby Football Union (CRFU) ceasing operation and no governing body, an executive committee of the ORFU and QRFU champion teams arranged a Dominion Final to be played in Montreal on November 15, 1888.
[src:1901-in-canadian-football/1888-in-canadian-football] Ottawa College and the Montreal Football Club played to a 0–0 tie.
[src:1901-in-canadian-football/1888-in-canadian-football] With Montreal outplaying Ottawa College in the second half, they suggested an overtime period, but Ottawa declined and the 1888 championship ended in a tie.
[src:1901-in-canadian-football/1901-in-canadian-football] The ORFU stated that all players must sign amateur cards.
[src:1901-in-canadian-football/1901-in-canadian-football] The CRU ruled that the ball was to be placed on the ground in line with the front foot of the Scrimmage before the lines could come together.
[src:1901-in-canadian-football/1901-in-canadian-football] John Thrift Meldrum Burnside's revised football rules were put into play in the University of Toronto Inter-faculty games, and later in the Mulock Cup championship games.
